# Documentation policy (EN + pt-BR)

**Rule:** All user-facing documentation **MUST** exist in **Brazilian Portuguese** and be **kept in sync** with the **English source of truth**, while reflecting the **actual source**: the **source code**, **functionalities**, and **capabilities** of the application. When you add or change docs, update EN first (to match code and behaviour), then sync the pt-BR file so structure and coverage stay aligned.

- **Not European Portuguese (pt-PT):** Files **`*.pt_BR.md`** and operator-facing **pt-BR prose** must follow **Brazil** usage, not Portugal. Prefer: **arquivo** (not *ficheiro*), **compartilhamento / compartilhar** (not *partilha / partilhar*), **padrão** or **por padrão** for “default” (not *defeito / por defeito* in IT sense), **seção** (not *secção*), **executar** or **rodar** for running commands (avoid *correr* for software). Orthography: follow **Brazilian** norms where they differ from Portugal (e.g. **canônico**). Assistant chat narrative: **`AGENTS.md`** (Brazilian Portuguese for explanations).

- **Source of truth (order):** **Code and application behaviour** are the deepest source of truth (config, API, CLI, capabilities). The **English (EN)** doc is the **canonical written** source and must accurately reflect the code and behaviour. **Brazilian Portuguese (pt-BR)** is the translation and must stay in sync with the EN version (same structure and coverage).
- **Location:** Put new application documentation (guides, reference, branding) under **docs/** and link from docs/README.md. Keep at repo root only what GitHub/tooling expect (README, SECURITY, CONTRIBUTING, CODE_OF_CONDUCT, LICENSE, NOTICE). Do not move **.github/** or **.cursor/**; pointer READMEs (deploy/, tests/) or deprecated notices (database/, scanners/) may stay next to code.
- **New documentation:** Any **new** user-facing doc (guides, reference, deploy, testing, observability, etc.) must exist in **both English and Brazilian Portuguese**. **Exception:** Plan files (e.g. `docs/plans/PLAN_*.md`, `docs/plans/PLANS_TODO.md`, `docs/plans/completed/`, `.cursor/plans/`) may be **English-only**. When adding a new doc: create the EN file first, add it to **docs/README.md** (index table) with both language links when pt-BR exists, then create the pt-BR file with the same structure and a language switcher at the top.
- **Planning vs product (links):** Do **not** add markdown links from user-facing guides into `docs/plans/` or `.cursor/plans/`; use **docs/README.md** *Internal and reference* and **`.cursor/rules/audience-segmentation-docs.mdc`**. CI: **`tests/test_docs_external_no_plan_links.py`**.
- **When behaviour changes:** Update the **English** doc first so it matches code and behaviour, then **sync the pt-BR** file so structure and coverage stay aligned.

## Navigability (no dead ends)

Documentation must be **navigable to and from** other documents so that:

- Readers do not hit **dead ends** (a doc that does not link onward to related topics).
- Operators can **discover** further details when learning the application.
- The goal is to make it **easy for operators** to learn how to use the app, what it is capable of doing, and how to get it working properly.

When writing or updating a doc: link **out** to related docs (usage, deploy, testing, troubleshooting, compliance, etc.) where the topic is mentioned; ensure the **docs/README.md** index and in-doc cross-links let readers move between topics and languages without getting stuck.

## Language switcher and EN ↔ pt-BR links (required)

Whenever a doc has a **Brazilian Portuguese** version (as it should for all user-facing docs except plan files), **both directions** of the link are required:

- **In EN files:** At the top (right after the title), add `**Português (Brasil):** [Filename.pt_BR.md](Filename.pt_BR.md)` (or path-relative, e.g. `[deploy/DEPLOY.pt_BR.md](deploy/DEPLOY.pt_BR.md)` from `docs/`).
- **In pt-BR files:** At the top, add `**English:** [Filename.md](Filename.md)` (or path-relative).

So: **EN always links to pt-BR** when pt-BR exists, and **pt-BR always links to EN**. This allows readers in either language to switch and avoids dead ends when only one language is open.

## Discoverability and cross-links

When a doc mentions a topic that has its own dedicated doc, **link to that doc**. If that doc exists in both languages, provide **both links** so the user can switch easily:

- Example (from an EN doc): `[DEPLOY.md](deploy/DEPLOY.md) ([pt-BR](deploy/DEPLOY.pt_BR.md))`
- Example (from a pt-BR doc): `[DEPLOY.pt_BR.md](deploy/DEPLOY.pt_BR.md) ([EN](deploy/DEPLOY.md))`

Typical cross-link targets: deploy (Docker, Kubernetes), testing, topology, commit/PR, compliance frameworks, sensitivity detection, adding connectors, usage. The main index is **docs/README.md**.

## Locale guard (pt-BR vs pt-PT)

After substantive edits to **`*.pt_BR.md`**, run **`uv run pytest tests/test_docs_pt_br_locale.py -v`** so common **European Portuguese** markers (e.g. *ficheiro*, *partilhar*, *secção*, *utilizador*, *tem de*, *continua a usar*) do not slip back in. The scan includes **`docs/private/**/*.pt_BR.md`** when that tree exists locally (same bar as markdown lint for operator notes). See **`.cursor/rules/docs-pt-br-locale.mdc`** for the preference table and how to extend the scan (e.g. tracked pitch/website YAML).

